tagExtract.example1:
Works aims to free users from a large amount of repetitive and mechanized manual operations, helping them easily and automatically handle business processes and tasks. It provides users with an intuitive and flexible tool, allowing them to create automated processes in a code free or low code manner, thereby improving work efficiency, simplifying daily tasks, and promoting digital transformation.
	The usage scenarios of Works are very wide, suitable for various organizations and industries. Here are some common usage scenarios:
	1. Automated data transmission and processing: for example, automatically saving attachments when receiving new emails; Or periodically extract data from one folder and copy or move it to another folder.
	2. Process automation: For example, creating approval processes, automatically notifying relevant personnel, and tracking approval progress; Or automatically trigger and execute specific business processes, such as document publishing process, product quotation review, etc.
	3. Notification and reminder: For example, when a specific event occurs, automatically send emails, text messages, or notifications to relevant personnel; Or trigger reminders based on specific conditions to help users handle important transactions in a timely manner.
	4. Data analysis and report generation: For example, regularly generating data reports and automatically sending them to relevant personnel; Or monitor specific indicators and automatically trigger an alarm when the preset threshold is reached.
	5. Intelligent document processing: For example, using intelligent technology to extract document information, automatically adding tags to documents, cataloging and other metadata.
	The product value of Works is mainly reflected in the following aspects:
	1. Automated Flows: Users can easily create Automated Flows using drag and drop editing with the mouse, such as automated data synchronization, generating summaries, sending notifications, etc., thereby reducing manual operations and improving work efficiency.
	2. Low code development: Works supports either no code or low code development methods, allowing both developers and non developers to participate in the creation and management of automated processes, reducing technical barriers.
	3. Support for multiple document operations: Works supports multiple triggering methods and document processing connectors, which can automatically process various types of documents, meeting the needs of document automation processing and circulation in different scenarios.
	4. Improve work efficiency: By automating tasks and processes, Works can help users save time and energy, allowing them to focus on more valuable work.
	5. Promoting digital transformation: Works can help organizations better utilize digital tools and technologies, improve the efficiency and flexibility of business processes, and drive the process of digital transformation.
	In summary, the product positioning of Works is to help users simplify workflow, improve work efficiency, and drive digital transformation. By automating routine tasks and processes, users can save time and energy, enabling them to focus on more valuable work, thereby achieving sustained personal and organizational growth and success.
tagExtract.example2:
Works forms a self running workflow by connecting different functions and operation modules together. In order to automate document processing and workflows, we first need to understand the logic of automated flows, which is: automatically executing the specified execution action when the set Trigger Event occurs. There are two fundamental concepts involved here: Trigger and Action.
	1. Trigger Event: A Trigger Event is the starting point of an automated workflow, and is used as the starting judgment for whether the automated process is executed based on the state change of the Trigger Event. For example, when uploading a file to the knowledge base, tags are automatically added to the file based on its content. In this case, uploading a file to the knowledge base is the Trigger Event of the process.
	Common Trigger include event triggering, timed triggering, and manual triggering. Below, we will take you to understand the differences and scenarios of these types of Trigger:
	① Event triggering: By setting a specified action event as the triggering action. It is generally applicable to scenarios where data creation or change operations need to be performed on files and folders, that is, when selecting the target folder and performing upload, copy, move, or delete actions under that folder, the next step of the operation can be executed. Example: When creating a new folder, automatically add the folder name to the catalog template.
	② Timed triggering: By setting specific time periods or time points as Trigger, such as fixed cycles every x hours, every day, or every week. In practical work, there are some tasks that need to be completed at specific times, mainly suitable for scenarios such as message reminders, and the time and frequency of workflow operation can be specified. Example: Automatically remind project leaders to update progress on a weekly basis, regularly backup data to designated folders, etc.
	③ Manual triggering: Manual triggering requires you to manually click run after setting up the automation task to trigger the next execution action. Unlike event triggering, manual triggering targets files or folders that have already been uploaded to a certain folder, and then manually clicks to perform the next action. For example, if you have completed writing a planning plan, you can right-click and select it to trigger the workflow, achieving automatic review and publication of the planning plan.
	2. Action Event refers to the operation performed after meeting the triggering conditions. If we want the process to execute smoothly as required, we need to set the actions that need to be executed after the process is triggered. A workflow can include multiple operations.
	In addition to the above two items, you can also set execution conditions.
	The execution condition is also known as a logical action, and only when this condition is met will the set operation be executed further. Simply put, it refers to a branch in a workflow, and the running order of the branch is matched from left to right. The process of that branch is only executed when the current branch condition is met. Example: When the content of a file contains "key information", the file is classified as confidential; When the keyword is not included in the file content, set the confidentiality level to non confidential.
	By setting up a workflow through "Trigger Event", "Action Event", and "branch", repetitive and simple workflows can be automated!
tagExtract.example3:
In order to make document processing more intelligent, Works has introduced Custom AI，  providing you with the ability to integrate and utilize artificial intelligence in your workflow. By combining Custom AI, workflow has expanded to a richer range of business scenarios. Next, you will learn about Custom AI.
	You can enter Works page and see the Custom AI page. The Custom AI page is used to display the AI models used in the workflow, supporting you in testing, experiencing, creating, and training. Simply put, if the workflow is a two handed process that can input data from one application into another, then Custom AI are its brain that can extract information from data sources. At present, there are many requirements in our workflow. In order to handle unstructured data such as general documents and tables, as well as structured data such as ID cards, business licenses, value-added tax invoices, and train ticket recognition, we have introduced built-in Custom AI into the workflow. The built-in Custom AI provides an out of the box way of use, allowing you to quickly use it in your workflow without the need for collecting sample data, generating, training, and publishing. In order to enable artificial intelligence to understand professional documents, we provide customized Custom AI that require you to upload your own data. Through simple annotation, training, and optimization, you can fine tune and configure it according to your needs based on the basic capabilities. For example, by adding a small number of sample documents, annotating the text information that needs to be extracted, and finally creating Custom AI that are suitable for business scenarios, the trained capabilities can be released and used in the workflow.
	The following are common application scenarios for Custom AI:
	Firstly, an important application scenario of Custom AI in workflow is "text recognition", which can help you extract text information from documents and images. You can use text recognition to automate the processing of various documents, such as contracts, invoices, resumes, papers, reports, etc. By extracting textual information, you can perform data analysis, archiving, and sharing more quickly, thereby accelerating business processes and improving work efficiency.
	Secondly, Custom AI also provide "tag extraction" functionality, which utilizes artificial intelligence technology to automatically analyze text and help you extract keywords from the text. You can use the tag extraction function to automatically extract the core tags of documents, enabling faster document classification, storage, retrieval, and management.
	Overall, the application scenarios and value of Custom AI in Works are multifaceted. It provides powerful custom Custom AI to help you achieve smarter and more efficient ways of working.

guidePage.text1: In this part, you will learn:
guidePage.text3: The Automated Flow is a service that automates the repetitive and mechanized tasks to improve your content processing efficiency.
guidePage.text4: What can I do with Automated Flow?
guidePage.text5: In some business scenarios, processing a large amount of data such as copying, moving or deleting files by manual wastes time and energy, which can easily go wrong. With automated flows, you can collaborate with other colleagues, extract file content, collect data, sync data, get notifications, and much more.
guidePage.text6: For example, you can automate these tasks:
guidePage.text7: Start an approval when a file is uploaded in a target folder
guidePage.text8: When creating a new folder, add catalogue to this folder
guidePage.text9: Save the attachment of the sheet file to a specified directory
guidePage.text10: Archive the files based on their time of creation
guidePage.text11: Automate your business flows with 30+ actions and 10+ templates. No code required.
guidePage.understandingText1: In the previous part we learned about the overview and different scenarios of automated flow. Here we'll introduce some basic concepts to you before building your own flow.
guidePage.understandingText4: The trigger event is the beginning of a flow, and the status of which is used to judge whether to start to perform a flow. In the above example, "upload a new file on Knowledge Documents" is the starting point of this flow.
guidePage.understandingText5.1: The most commonly used trigger event types are:
guidePage.understandingText5.2: By event, By manual, After form completion and By schedule
guidePage.understandingText6.1: By event: Set the specified event as the trigger, mostly applied to the scenarios where
guidePage.understandingText6.3: is involved in dealing with files and folders. In other words, you need to select a target folder, and when you create, upload, copy, move or delete a file under this folder, perform the next action. For example, when creating a folder, add the name of the folder to the catalogue template automatically.
guidePage.understandingText7.1: By manual: Trigger by manual refers to the process of manually clicking after setting up an automated task in order to perform the next action. Different from triggering by event, the object that is manually triggered is a file or folder that has already been uploaded to a certain folder so that you click "Run" to trigger the next action required. It is mainly used in scenarios involving
guidePage.understandingText7.3: . For example: A folder which was created long time ago is stored in Documents and can be automatically archived to another specified folder.
guidePage.understandingText8.1: After form completion: Set form submission as a trigger event, suitable for scenarios where forms are used for
guidePage.understandingText8.3: , such as document permission application, circulation management of approved contract files, and initiation of quota expansion application by filling out forms.
guidePage.cronText1.1: By schedule: The trigger event would be a fixed time period or time point, which can be applied to the
guidePage.cronText1.3: scenarios. During the office work, some tasks are required to be done in a specified time like when you need to archive the files to a target location regularly, you should select the time and interval to trigger this task and this task will run every x minute(s), x month(s), x year(s), etc.
guidePage.understandingText10.3: , and only when this condition is met will the set action event be performed. Simply put, it refers to the
guidePage.understandingText10.5: in a flow. The running order of the branch is matched from left to right, and only when the condition of the previous branch is met can the process of next branch be executed. In the above example, "approved → upload the file" can be understood as Branch 1 in the process. If the approval is not approved, the file will be deleted, and then "approved → deleted the file" is Branch 2.
guidePage.understandingText12: Action event refers to the specified action run by the flow automatically after the previous trigger event occurs and the conditions are met. In the above case, after the approval is passed, "upload the file in Knowledge Documents" is the action the flow performs in the end.
guidePage.text12: You may start your automated flow just by setting the "trigger" and "action".
guidePage.text14: A trigger is an event that starts an automated flow. Say when uploading a file, add tags to this file—the trigger would be "uploading a file". The trigger is  the beginning of the flow, and only one trigger can be configured during this flow, which cannot be deleted as well.
guidePage.text16: An action is after the trigger event happens, the specific event that is performed for processing or delivering data. Say you want to inform relevant staff when the file is being updated—the action would be "inform relevant staff". In the same flow, you may set one or more actions.
guidePage.text17: How can I create and administer a flow?
guidePage.text18: Three simple ways for you to create a flow:
guidePage.text19.2: Create totally custom flows via the following methods:
guidePage.text20: By event: Set the specified event as the trigger. For example, when your colleagues require sending approval message to you when they perform actions on the files under the designated folder, you may set the actions such as create, move, delete, copy as the trigger event to move on to the next step.
guidePage.text21: By manual: After finishing setting up an automated task, you need to click the Run button before the next action is performed.
guidePage.text22: After form completion: Set the submission of form as the trigger. For instance, when users need to request for the expansion of space quota, they should submit the application form first, and then trigger the approval flow.
guidePage.text23.2: We have provided some templates of the most commonly used automated tasks in [Templates] to help you deal with all kinds of business scenarios.
guidePage.text24.2: When you need to personalize a task, you may choose to import the template package from local to make it more convenient for you to finish the task.
guidePage.text25: You may click [My flows] from the top bar of [Works] to administer the flows created by you and view the flows that are assigned to you.
guidePage.text26: Now, try and create your first automated flow!

guidePage.modelText2: Integrating AI Models into Automated Flow
guidePage.modelText5: Automated Flow: Build automated flows customized for your business.
guidePage.modelText6: Combined with the AI Model capability, including Large Language Model, OCR Model and Automatic Extraction Model, the Models are introduced into Works to deal with more business scenarios. Here are the brief introductions of each model:
guidePage.modelText7.2: is a deep learning based technique that utilizes a large amount of textual data for training to acquire rich language-related knowledge. The ability of this model can be fully applied in our flows, such as text summaries, meeting minutes summaries, etc.
guidePage.modelText8.2: is a technique used to convert text in images into computer-readable formats, including image pre-processing and feature extraction. With this model, text recognition can be automatically performed on images or PDF files, and can be applied in business scenarios such as extracting information from invoices or IDs, general text recognition, etc.
guidePage.modelText9.2: can automatically identify and extract key information from data, thereby improving the efficiency and accuracy of data processing, which can be applied in customized scenarios, such as extracting labels or custom information from documents.
guidePage.modelText10: Next, you will learn more about our Models.
guidePage.modelText11: The Models is a like a storehouse that is used to display the AI models applied in the automated flow, supporting users to test the effectiveness of the models, and later supporting users to create and train models. Simply put, if a flow is like two hands that can input data from one app into another, then an AI model is its brain that can extract information from unstructured data sources.
guidePage.modelText12.1: At present, there are many scenarios in our automated flow. In order to process unstructured data such as documents and images, as well as structured data such as ID, business licenses, value-added tax invoices, and train ticket recognition, we have introduced prebuilt AI capabilities into the flow. The
guidePage.modelText12.3: can be quickly integrated into your flow without the need for data collection, generation, training, and posting.
guidePage.modelText13.1: In order to empower the model to understand professional documents, we provide customized AI capabilities that require you to upload your own data, annotate, train, and optimize the AI model. For example, by uploading a small number of sample documents, annotating the text information to be extracted, and finally creating a
guidePage.modelText13.3: that fits the business scenario, the trained version can be released and used in your flow.
guidePage.modelText14: Click [Models], select a pre-trained model, e.g.: Summarize Information from Posted File, and then click [Select a file to test].
guidePage.modelText15: Select [Apply to Flow], then a flow that uses the LLM to extract the key information of the file and automatically generates a file to be posted will be generated.
